  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 11.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "When thou with rebukes dost correct man for iniquity",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The calamities which God sends on a man are of the nature of \"rebukes\" addressed to his spirit. They are intended to teach, instruct, warn, deter from evil-doing (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 36:8-10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou makest his beauty to consume away like a moth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or, \"thou dost consume, as by a moth, what he prizes;\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " his health, his strength, \"all wherein he has joy and satisfaction\" (Hengstenberg). As a moth corrodes a beautiful garment, so does thy displeasure and heavy hand pressing on him corrode and destroy all which constituted his delight and glory. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Surely every man is vanity",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp. ver. 5 ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ad",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " fin.). This has become a sort of refrain, terminating the second as well as the first part of the psalm (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 107:8, 15, 21, 31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 2:1, 11, 15, 19, 21, 23, 26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 9:12, 17, 21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Psalm 39:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
